{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5d58cdb8-a879-428e-83cc-7a6e5f290af2","content":"The standard .NET approach is to use the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package. It provides an `IFileSystem` interface that wraps all those static calls, and a `MockFileSystem` for tests.\n\nHere's how to refactor your `ReportGenerator`:\n\n**1. Inject `IFileSystem` instead of calling statics directly:**\n\n```csharp\n// Before:  File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n// After:   _fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);\n```\n\n**2. In tests, use `MockFileSystem`:**\n\n```csharp\nvar fs = new MockFileSystem();\nvar gen = new ReportGenerator(fs);\ngen.GenerateReport(\"test\");\nAssert.True(fs.File.Exists(\"/tmp/reports/test_....txt\"));\n```\n\nWould you like me to refactor `ReportGenerator.cs` to use `System.IO.Abstractions`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"81a49ca3-3bfd-431d-acb4-222342d6f8fd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I understand the project. The user has a `ReportGenerator` class that directly uses static `File` and `Directory` methods, making it hard to test. The standard .NET approach is to use `System.IO.Abstractions` or create your own interface wrapping the file system calls.\n\nThe best approach for .NET is to use the `System.IO.Abstractions` NuGet package, which provides `IFileSystem` interface that wraps all `System.IO` static methods. This is the most widely-used and battle-tested approach.\n\nLet me recommend the approach and implement it.","outputTokens":372,"requestId":"CFD6:180DF7:6157DC3:6D0CE38:69EC1C97"},"id":"6c891d1a-a6e9-4ad5-84e6-aa1f01a29e21","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:45:03.706Z","parentId":"49af92c4-5b1e-4acb-89f8-af6a19abcb71"}
